default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultThe Palestine General Federation of Trade Unions default(PGFTU)defaultThe PGFTU is a national trade union centre with an estimated membership of 290,000, and is affiliated with the ITUC. The union in its current form is historically aligned with F
defaultatah, but other parties have also worked within its organisation
defaultThe PGFTU traces its modern history to 1965, under Jordanian control of the West Bank, as the successor to the Arab Labourers Society that had been set up in 1921 in Haifa. Its current 
defaultgeneral secretary is Shaher Sa
default'
defaulted, who has held the position for many years. The PGFTU consists of 13 national unions, each with regional and local organizations, in sectors such as Hotels/Tourism, 
defaultHealthcare
default, Textile/Clothing and Construction. 
default&#xa0;
defaultC
defaultooperation between the two federations started in 1993 after the signing of the Oslo Accords between Israel and the PLO.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultIn 1995 the Histadrut and the PGFTU 
defaultsigned a precedent-setting agreement 
defaultthat the Histadrut would 
defaultprovide legal representation to Palestinians working for Israeli employers. The PGFTU were to receive 50 per cent of all 
defaulttrade union
default 
defaultfees 
defaultcollected 
defaultfrom Palestinian employees working in Israel.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultHowever, the arrangement froze due to the deteriorating poli
defaulttical and security conditions
default at the end of 2000
default. Differences emerged between the two parties about how much money the Histadrut still owed the PGFTU.
default&#xa0;
default This became increasingly difficult to evaluate over time as the number of Palestinians working in Israel
default significantly dropped during the second intifada.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultA number of critics of Israel within the trade union movement, especially in the UK and Ireland, emphasised the disagreement; repeatedly using it as a justification for promoting trade union boycotts, di
defaultsinvestment and sanctions against Israel.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultHowever, throughout even the most difficult times, the two organisations continued to have dialogue. In time, improved relations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority led to better union to union cooperati
defaulton. 
default defaultAt the Histadrut’s 2007 annual Congress, the PGFTU was officially represented and the delegation present affirmed its commitment to maintain and extend constructive relations.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultIn October 2007 the Histadrut successfully petitioned Israel’s High Court
default of Justice for Israeli labour law to be applied in the occupied territories.
default&#xa0;
default Nine judges ruled that Palestinians working for Israeli employers in West Bank settlements should be given the same work benefits provided
default to Israeli workers
default by Israeli law.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultI
defaultn another program of joint cooperation, over 20 Israeli and Palestinian transport union representatives signed a number of agreements at a bilateral meeting organised by the International Transport Workers’ Federation (ITF) in June 2007.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultThe Histadrut an
defaultd the PGFTU continue to meet under the auspices of the ITF.
default&#xa0;
default In February 2008, both parties agreed to facilitate the passage of professional drivers at checkpoints and road blocks in the West Bank.
default&#xa0;defaultOn 24 July 2008, a landmark agreement was reached between the Histadrut and the PGFTU. Facilitated by the International Trade Union Confederation (ITUC) to which both are affiliated, the agreement ‘a
defaultimed at increased protection of Palestinian workers and advancing fraternity and coexistence between the Israeli and Palestinian peoples.’  
