defaultThe 2008 Histadrut and the PGFTU Agreement calls on the intdefaulternational trade unions to build links not break them.defaultThe Histadrut and the PGFTU made a direct appeal to the international movement in their 2008 agreement. Clause 5 states ‘It is agreed by the parties that relations between the Israeli and Palestinian t
defaultrade unions shall be based on negotiations, dialogue, and the conduct of meetings and joint projects (e.g. professional courses and workshops) that will promote the rights of Israeli and Palestinian workers and pensioners and will advance fraternity and co
default-existence between the two peoples.’ Crucially, for UK trade unionists, clause 6 ‘
defaultcall[s] for support from ITUC and its affiliates throughout the world, and other trade unions throughout the world and other international organisations in order to fulfil thdefaulte provisions of defaultthe defaultclause default&#xa0;
defaultThe Histadrut
default 
defaultreleased a statement to the world-wide trade union movement outlining its supp
defaultort for a two-state solution, Israeli and Palestinian workers’ rights and its developing relationship with Palestinian trade unions.
defaultThe Histadrut urges “the Israeli government and the Palestinian Authority (PA) to immediately resume their negotiations,” 
defaultand says it understands and is concerned “by the effects the restrictions on movement and the security fence/wall can have on the lives of Palestinian workers and their families”.
default&#xa0;
default The federation says it supports the decision to remove security checkpoints
default in the context of the renewed security situation and calls upon the “Israeli government to dismantle all illegal outposts”.
defaultThe statement goes on to say that the Histadrut recognises these problems and steadfastly works with the Palestine General Federati
defaulton of Trade Unions (PGFTU) to mitigate them whilst negotiations on the wider issues take place.
defaultIsraeli and Palestinian trade unions have been successfully working together and signing 
defaultco-operation agreements
default over the last few years, and the Histadrut’s statement says it is their duty, as trade unionists, to be involved with the peace process and serve 
defaultas role-models. 
defaultThe Histadrut says: “
defaultThe ongoing conflict between Israel and Palestine is very complex and our goal is to reach an understanding and to look for common denominators. We believe that the only way to overcome the hostility is through peace a
defaultnd trust, such as that which exists today between the Histadrut and the PGFTU.”
defaultGuy Ryder, the
default then
default ITUC General Secretary hailed the Histadrut 
defaultstatement
default as 
default"an important and welcome call for dialogue and progress to achieve the objective of two states co-existing in conditions of peace and security, and full respect for the rights of all working people.” He 
defaultsaid Israeli-Palestinian
default trade union co-operation has an important “contribution to make in promoting peace and mutual understanding in the Middle East.”
